  "market_context": "Gold (apoZ/GC1!) on 1-hour chart around June 22-24, 2025, trading in the 3,310-3,425 range. A bullish daily candle closure sets up an expected gap up and continuation, followed by a bearish daily close that flips the next-day expectation.",
  "key_observation": "After a bullish daily closure, price gaps up and hits the previous day high target before falling back into range and closing bearish — then the next bearish daily setup produces an expansion lower that sweeps the low and forms a consolidation/retracement rather than a reversal.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a bullish daily candle closure forming a bullish setup for the next day.",
    "Step 2: Noted that on a bullish setup price gapped up and hit the first target — the previous day's high.",
    "Step 3: Observed price fell back into the range after hitting the target, forming low resistance lows and closing bearish on the daily.",
    "Step 4: Applied the EQ logic — because of the bearish daily close, expected price to open and trade lower the next day.",
    "Step 5: Confirmed that price did open and trade lower, sweeping the prior low.",
    "Step 6: Assessed whether the large-range move would produce a reversal or a consolidation/retracement — concluded it was a consolidation/retracement.",
    "Step 7: Validated the sweep with a closure and anticipated the large-range / small-range / large-range expansion sequence, which played out with another large expansion lower.",
    "Step 8: Noted price traded back up into the EQ and began consolidating, suggesting caution before seeking a new setup."
  ],
  "outcome": "Bullish daily setup hit its first target (previous day high) on the gap up; subsequent bearish daily close produced expected expansion lower with the low sweep validated by closure, followed by another large-range continuation.",
  "lessons": "Daily candle closures set the bias for next-day delivery: bullish closes gap up and target the previous day high, while bearish closes expect expansion lower. After a large-range expansion, expect a small range (consolidation/retracement) before another large range, not an immediate reversal.",
